				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="EL">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						πάντων κρα -
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						κράτιστος.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						Vt Caesaris,
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="Julius Caesar"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<language ident="EL">
				<position book_orientation="0" place="tail">
					<marginalia_text>
						τὸ πρωτέυειν.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The declared goal of Cicero, to be the best of all men.
				Just as the goal of Cicero is to be the first among all men.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
		<marginalia hand="Italian">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="left_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						Nemo vnq[uam] satis prudens, aut fortis fuit: aut quod tertium est, satis dulcis:
						quem nihil perturbaret, aut offenderet, quicquid accideret turbarum. [T]am industria, 
						effectus est prudentia[e], et fortitudinis:
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
				<position book_orientation="0" place="intext">
					<marginalia_text>
						nec vllum noui satis industrium.
					</marginalia_text>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				No one was every prudent or strong enough (or sweet enough which is the third option),
				whom nothing would have bothered or offended if some turmoil had occurred. 
				Such industria is the effect of prudence and strength; I know that no industry is sufficient enough.
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		<marginalia book_id="FolgersHa2" hand="Italian" id="Ha2.091v_0001" marginalia_continues_to="Ha2.092r_0001" marginalia_to_transcription="Ha2.092r.xml">
			<language ident="LA">
				<position book_orientation="90" place="right_margin">
					<marginalia_text>
						{ Gulielmi Birdi dictum de Axiophilo. Illum hominem nunq[uam] vidi iratum; nunq[uam] [A4[r]: tristem; nunq[uam] timidum; nunq[uam] irresolutum; nunq[uam] ignavum, aut languidum; nunq[uam]
						sui, aut aliorum immemorem; nunq[uam] perturbatum vllo Casu. Non noui hominem, beneficioru[m] magis memorem; aut iniuriarum magis
						immemore[m]. Nec scio alique[m], cuius
						rationes, et actiones ità dependent
						à Seipso. Ha[e]c ille sobrius generosus 
						de Axiophilo ingenuè.]
						<!-- Continues onto facing page, left margin, Ha2.092r -->
					</marginalia_text>
					<person name="William Bird"/>
					<person name="Axiophilus"/>
				</position>
			</language>
			<translation>
				The saying of William Bird regarding Axiophilus. I never saw that man angry, never [A4[r]: sad, never timid, never irresolute, never lazy or languid, never forgetful of himself or of others, 
				never disturbed by any happening. I have never known a man more mindful of favors, or
				more forgetful of injuries. Nor do I know of anyone whose reasons and actions depend so much
				on himself. The sensible noble, man naturally finds these things in Axiophilus.]
			</translation>
		</marginalia>
		
